Do you have furniture with Formica that has seen better days, but you don’t want to deal with the hassle of replacing it? Of course you could paint it, but I wanted the inside of this cabinet to look cohesive, that’s why I refinished this drop down door to match the existing wood. 
This was my first time trying @retiqueliquidwood. I had been wanting to test it out for the longest time. All I can see is that I already have another piece I want to try it on. I’ve tried other faux wood techniques and the big difference with this one, is the way it feels, it really feels like wood.

Sometimes you need to choose what’s best for the piece! And even though a darker color was not my initial choice, just like most of you who voted in my stories, at the end I had to chose the finish that would last longer. The darker wood inside with a moody color on the outside seemed like a better alternative. 
If this piece was in my house, it would definitely be a coffee bar, as you know, I’m a major coffee lover. 

How would you use it in your home? Overall, I love the vintage look it has, the black glaze made a huge difference!

Did you know that steel decomposes in approximately 50 years, while it can take up to 200 years for aluminium to break down? 

After doing some research, I found that this industrial metal brown swivel Domore chair probably goes back to the 1940’s. I can’t help but wonder where it spent most of its life before I found it. 
This chair was buried among several others at the thrift store. The imperfect metal, the old brand tag under the seat just drew me in, and once I tried picking it up, the heaviness made it even cooler.  What’s the coolest or the most unexpected thrifted find you have ever encounter?

Don’t forget to remember why you started, was it because you were hoping to see something beautiful after you were done? Was it because you wanted to be mindful of the household budget and at the same time bring charm into your home or space? Or perhaps you just wanted to be part of some kind of transformation, it didn’t matter what kind it was. Whatever the reason, I’m convince that an internal and very personal DIY project takes place before we can externalize that into our home projects. But, we usually don’t take that into count before we start because we are focused on the end result. The reality is that the process can be messy, unpredictable, time consuming, and may I say, personally transformative. This is your reminder to breath, enjoy the process and keep your eyes on the final goal.

There’s no way to refinish furniture in a way that everyone will like. Thank goodness we all have a different taste and opinions, otherwise life would be boring. If you have been here for a while, I’m grateful for you. And if you’re new, you must know that I’ve restored pieces to it’s original state, but a lot of the time I paint wood, even when it’s in good condition - it doesn’t happen often because most of the time the piece needs and screams for paint - but when I paint wood that’s in good condition, I do it without apologizing, and just because I want to, or because my customer wants me to. 

I like trying different painting techniques that fit within my style, but here and there I will push my own boundaries. At times, I end up surprising myself by how much I like something I didn’t expect to like. And other times times, I scratch my head and think “yeah, I’m not doing that again.” 

Anyways, in this feed you will see furniture that’s different to your taste, and once in a while even different to my own, and guess what? It’s completely ok. We will keep trying new things, we will keep nailing it, failing, enjoying, working, evolving and painting.

This pair was painted in green to honor the life of Jen from @perfectlyimperfectfurnitureres niece, Hanna. And also, to bring mental health awareness.
This hits close to home since I’ve struggled with my own mental health in the past. 

If you struggle with mental health, remember this:

•You’re enough and worthy of love

•Your struggle is a part of you, but it doesn’t have to define you

•Stop shoving and stuffing feelings, acknowledge them, sometimes they need to be honored, other times they need to be challenged. 

•Your emotions are signals, and many times they’re telling you that an environment, or a belief needs to change

•Your ability to make things happen, or being productive doesn’t determine your value as a person. 

•It’s ok to say “I need help” or to simply say “no” without guilt. 

•If you don’t believe in God, that’s fine, but if you do, know that God doesn’t love you any less on your worst day. He is there and He is near, regardless of what you’re feeling. 

May we continue to refurbish our lives one day at a time. Taking away the old, and renewing our minds one thought at a time.

My grandma was a true gem, and the desire of working on one of her pieces of furniture comes often. At the age of 82 she learned how to paint on canvas with oil paint, talk about never being too old to start something new. And she was amazingly good at it. 

She passed alway several years ago, before I started refinishing furniture. By the time I was doing this, her house and belongings had already been given to other family members. I think this is why it makes me happy when other people keep their loved ones furniture as a way to remember them. 

To this day, my grandma is one of the kindest and most loving people I’ve ever known, I was blessed to be her granddaughter.

🚨Products used listed below🚨 It’s amazing how a few simple steps can do so much to revive your wore out furniture.

1. To clean the chairs I mixed a little bit of Dawn dish soap to one cup of water. Making sure the bristles in my brush were soft to prevent the original finish from coming off, a gentle scrub is all they needed. Focusing on the grimy areas and where the dust was trapped, these chairs needed a good rinse. 

2. The scraper used to remove the crusty finish is from @bahcotools, but a 120 grit sanding sheet will do too! 

3. For the stain I used Premium Fast Dry in the color Dark Walnut from @varathane, this allowed me to finish the project the same day. 

4. Finally, to revive the wood and protect the touched up areas, I applied Furniture Finish from @walrusoil 

Remember to save this post for your upcoming furniture projects!

It’s not just paint! Colors can transform the feeling you get when entering a room while making furniture look brand new! And let’s not forget, its better for the earth. 

This pair of nightstands are part of a bedroom set that was bought at a big box store. The set was still in good condition, but the dark finish was flaking off, showing the lighter tone veneer underneath. And although we can all love a good all flaky finish on antiques, my clients were not loving it on this more modern looking one. I’m glad she opted to have them refinished rather than buying new ones, because we all play a part in saving one piece of furniture at a time from going to the landfills. 

For this makeover I custom mixed Midnight Blue and Ash, from @fusionmineralpaint.

I’ve said it before and I’ll say it again, refinishing furniture has been a huge part in my healing from disabling anxiety. With every project, my own life is refurbished from the inside out. 
Working with my hands keeps me in the present and what a huge gift that is! What you see in this account, is just a reflection of what I still go through day in and day out. 
Getting rid of the old and being transformed by the renewal of my mind. Today, anxiety is not longer holding me tight, but it takes prayer, it takes tenacity, it takes work, it takes a community, it takes truth. 
Transformation is not easy but necessary, acknowledging what needs to be work on and removing it to have a greater life. Furniture projects remind me of these things every day. 

More than ever, I’m grateful for what I get to do, and for all of the people (including you) that I get to be surrounded while doing it. Most importantly, I’m grateful to God, who allows me and gives me the ability to do what I’m so blessed to be doing.

✨DAY 1 of DIYing our fence✨because we have a wild Bernadoole dog with tons of energy that needs space to burn all her crazy out.

After bringing her home last fall and seeing her personality, we knew this project needed to get done ASAP! With winter around the corner, this was our last chance (this year) to tackle this project. 

Thankfully both my husband and I suffer from “howhardcanitbeitis” 😆 and went for it. 

We ended up having to rent an extension for the power auger so the holes for the post were deep enough.
Here is a list of supplies we used on this day: 

•Power Auger with extension (you can rent them by the hour, or day) 
•Pressure treated 4x4 posts
•For leveling: String line and level 
•Fast set concert mix
•Pea gravel 
•Water
•Grade stakes, drill and screws for braces
•And muscles, lots of muscles 😅💪🏽
